Species distribution modeling R Workshop I

Ally Phillimore


Introduction and Aims

Todays workshop involves running and critiquing a species distribution model. In this first SDM session we will work with presence/absence data, and then in the second session well move on to presence only data. One of the reasons for starting with presence/absence data is that we can use GLMs, which you will soon encounter on the Statistics and Data Analysis course. For anyone who is unsure of how they work please ask me in the session and I can go over it.

Well break down all the stages of species distribution modeling and do a lot of steps by hand so we get a clear idea of the logic.

This practical needs to start with a major acknowledgment in that most of it is a shortened version of an R practical written by an expert in the field Professor Damaris Zurell.

In this session we will cover the following steps that we discussed in the lectures:
1. Conceptualisation
2. Preparing data
3. Model fitting
4. Testing and critiquing the model
5. Making projections in time

Before we get started.

We will run the session today in R and R studio. Please ensure that you have a recent version of each on your computer. In R you will need to install the following packages.

geodata terra

1. Conceptualisation

Before we even get started we need to think about the study species/population, the data we have, the modeling approach we will adopt and the climate variables that may be important. We also need to think about the question we will be asking. In this practical we are going to focus on an upland bird and ask how the area of suitable climate is likely to change in the future.

Study species
Today we are going to work with a dataset on ring ouzel (Turdus torquatus). This is a summer migrant to European uplands and mountains. You can find out more about its ecology and where it is found in the UK from https://www.rspb.org.uk/birds-and-wildlife/wildlife-guides/bird-a-z/ring-ouzel/

If you want to see them, one or two pairs nest most years in the Pentland hills just outside Edinburgh.

Study population
Were going to work with a dataset on the presence/absence of this species in Switzerland. This dataset is based on a breeding bird atlas based on 3 visits a year to 1km grid cells from 1993-1996. These data were then used in Zurell et al.(2020) and made available to download from a data repository (https://datadryad.org/stash/dataset/doi:10.5061/dryad.k88v330). The dataset is available on Learn. Because our data come from a systematic survey we have information on absences as well as presences.

Putative climatic drivers
One of the first questions we need to ask ourselves is what climate variables are likely to be important determinants of ring ouzel population size. If we aready know a lot about the ecology we can use that information to guide our choice of variables.

However, as Im guessing none of us is expert in ring ouzel ecology what well do is adopt the climatic variables that Zurell et al (2020) found to be most predictive. This isnt really a strong justification if we were doing this analysis thoroughly, but it;s useful here as it should give us some fairly strong relationships between climate variables and presence/absence. We will focus on bio5 = maximum temperature of the warmest month, bio2 = mean diurnal range, bio14 = precipitation of driest month (all from https://www.worldclim.org/data/bioclim.html)

Question 1: You will be analysing presence/absence data using a generalized linear model (GLM), what distribution family should you choose? A GLM with binomial family errors should work well. A binary outcome is a special case of a binomial model.


Questions we should ask ourselves during the conceptualisation stage
- What biases may our dataset have?
- Do we expect our species to be at equilibrium with climate during the survey period?
- What impact do we expect each of our climate variables to have on our species and why? Are these effects of climate likely to be direct or indirect via impacts on resources?

This dataset contains data on 56 bird species across 2535 grid cells. It doesnt include spatial information (latitudes and longitudes), probably because some of this information is sensitive. But for our purposes today, this doesnt matter as locations have already been matched with climate data from worldclim.
Looking at the data summary above, familiarise yourself with the column names. What proportion of grid cells are ring ouzels found in?
You will notice a column with the header blockCVtile - this divides Switzerland into 5 regions and we will use it later for spatial cross validation.

For the future climate we can see (directly above) from the code that weve requested an SSP == 2, RCP=4.5 pathway and for the period 2040-2060. The climate projections come from the CMIP6 (Coupled Model Intercomparison Project Phase 6) dataset. The The resolution of grid cells is at 10 minutes, which in Switzerland is approx 12km. Weve used this global model (CNRM-CM6-1-HR), which is supposed to be quite well downscaled for Europe (in other words the global climate models are run at a coarser resolution and then models can be used to make the downscaled data a better fit to the landscape elevation etc), but there are a wide variety of different models we could choose from if we wanted to do ensemble forecasting.

Our next step is to reproject the raster data in Swiss coordinates and first crop the layers for the Swiss boundary. In the interest of time, I suggest we just copy and paste this code rather than looking in details at how it works.

# A spatial mask of Switzerland in Swiss coordinates

4. Testing and critiquing our model

4.1 Partial effects

The first step of model critique is to understand how each climate variable affects the presence/absence of ring ouzels. To do this we will plot the partial effects, i.e.the effects of each variable whilst holding the other variables constant.

We will achieve this by using the predict function for each variable. In order to use the predict function we will generate a new data frame in which our focal variable varies but the other variables are held constant.

Starting with bio_2

bio_2<-seq(min(ouzel_df$bio_2),max(ouzel_df$bio_2),0.1)

newdata_bio2<-expand.grid(bio_2,mean(ouzel_df$bio_5),mean(ouzel_df$bio_14))
names(newdata_bio2)<-c("bio_2","bio_5","bio_14")
#To use predict we need to generate a new dataset. We will set the other two climate variables at their mean.

response<-predict(model,newdata=newdata_bio2,type="response")
#We've told the predict function to make a prediction on the response scale, ie. in terms of presence/absence

plot(newdata_bio2$bio_2,response,type="l")

4.2 Spatial cross validation

Now were going to conduct spatial cross validation to examine how well our model can predict the presence/absence of ring ouzels in different blocks (see Fig 1). If you remmeber back to the lecture, this involves a few steps. (1) we randomly drop a block from the dataset. (2) We then refit the glm to this reduced training dataset. (3) Use the climate data in the ring ouzel dataset to obtain a predicted probability of ring ouzel presence. (4) Consider different probability thresholds to generate a ROC curve. (5) Calculate the area under the curve. And then repeat for each of the blocks.

In our case there are only 5 spatial blocks, so we will run the cross validation five times and calculate the AUC each time. From these five blocks we can then calculate an average AUC. You can find R functions to do all of this, but today well do all the steps ourselves to make sure we understand the process.

#first we will exclude spatial block 1.
training1<-subset(ouzel_df,blockCV_tile!=1)
#next we re-run the glm
model1<-glm( Turdus_torquatus ~ bio_2 + I(bio_2^2) + bio_5 + I(bio_5^2) + bio_14 + I(bio_14^2), family='binomial', data=training1)
#we will then subset the data for a testing dataset and we will see how well the glm fitted to the other data does in predicting presences in this testing block
testing<-subset(ouzel_df,blockCV_tile==1)
predicted<-predict(model1,testing,type="response")
#so here we have a prediction as a proportion rather than as a pres/abs.

#The next step is to take different threshold values (i.e probability values at which we count a species as present or absent)
thresholds<-seq(0,1,0.001)
tpr<-c()
fpr<-c()
#We will then use a loop to consider the true positive and false positive rate at each threshold value
for(x in 1:length(thresholds)){

predicted.pres<-as.numeric(predicted>thresholds[x])

present_correct<-length(which(predicted.pres*testing$Turdus_torquatus==1))
present_incorrect<-length(which(testing$Turdus_torquatus-predicted.pres==1))
tpr[x]<-present_correct/(present_correct+present_incorrect)

absent_correct<-length(which(predicted.pres+testing$Turdus_torquatus==0))
absent_incorrect<-length(which(testing$Turdus_torquatus-predicted.pres==-1))
fpr[x]<-absent_incorrect/(absent_incorrect+absent_correct)

}

#When we've run that we can plot the receiver operating characteristic (ROC) curve
plot(fpr,tpr,xlab="false positive rate, 1-sensitivity",ylab="true positive rate, specificity",type="l")
abline(0,1,lty=2)

#Finally to calculate AUC, we can imagine lots of small rectangles. For each one we will calculate its areas and then the area under curve is the sum of those

sortedvals<-cbind(fpr,tpr)[order(fpr),]

AUC<-0
for(x in 2:length(sortedvals[,1])){
  AUC<-AUC+(sortedvals[x,1]-sortedvals[x-1,1])*sortedvals[x-1,2]}

AUC
##       fpr 
## 0.9477802

This is quite a high AUC value, suggesting a good model performance when it comes to predicting ring ouzel presence/absence in another region. You could now repeat this process for the other blocks to calculate an average AUC (only if you want to).

We also want to decide on an optimal probability threshold, as well use this for the mapping stage that comes next. Below is one way of doing this

#Here we'll find a value that maximises true positive rate and minimises false positive rate
bestthreshold<-thresholds[which.max(tpr+(1-fpr))]

bestthreshold
## [1] 0.117
Question 4: Which would be better for spatial validation, dividing grid cells into training and testing at random or dividing grid cells into spatial blocks? Dividing grid cells into spatial blocks is better as then we are making predictions to a dataset that represents more of an extrapolation rather than interpolation.


5. Prediction

OK, weve convinced ourselves that the model is performing quite well. The final step is to predict where might be suitable for ring ouzels now and in the future.

The four ingredients that we needs are (i) the model, (ii) the climate layers that we imported from worldclim and (iii) the predict function that weve already used and (iv) the threshold we identified.

Well start with the current distribution.

bio_curr_df <- as.data.frame(bio_curr, xy = TRUE, na.rm = FALSE)

bio_curr_df$pred_glm<-predict(model,bio_curr_df,type="response")

# Make binary predictions:
bio_curr_df$bin_glm <- ifelse(bio_curr_df$pred_glm > bestthreshold, 1, 0)

#plot the current probability and predicted presence/absence.


r_pred_curr <- rast(as.matrix(bio_curr_df[,-c(3:5)]),type="xyz")
plot(r_pred_curr)
